In the above equation, the level of victimization of individual i is modeled to be determined by interpersonal trust (T); individual age (A), in nonlinear terms; gender (G); socio-economic status (captured by Sisben categories) (Y);
2
 and educational level (E). The selection of these variables is straightforward: interpersonal trust is the key variable whose potential effects on victimization we aim to test; age has been shown to clearly affect victimization as young people are more likely to be victims and perpetrators of crime; males are shown to perpetrate the vast majority of crimes while females are victims of some specific sex-related crimes. Education, as a proxy of human capital, may affect the probably of success of crime (thus increasing expected returns) but also reduce the probability of becoming a victim by increasing awareness and prevention against risky behaviors.
